max-width
The max-width property in CSS is used to define the maximum width of an element. 
The value of the width cannot be larger than the value by max-width. 
If the content is larger than the max-width then it will go to the next line and if the content is smaller than max-width then it has no effect.

min-width
The min-width property in CSS is used to define the minimum width of an element. 
The value of the width cannot be less than the value of min-width. 
If the content specified within the element is smaller, min-width maintains the specified minimum width.



-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Example:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<title>Online CSS Editor</title>
<head>

<style>
div{
    border:5px solid red;
    max-width:300px;
}
img{
    width:100%;                    //** When an image is added, the width might exceed the max-width we have specified. Using overflow property hides the image partially. 
                                        So we use image{width:100%} which takes the exact full width of its parent element without cropping out the image. Full image is visible within the specified width.
}
p{
    text-align:center;
    padding:10px;
}
</style>

</head>
<body>
<div>
